 Since  $\left|n x-1\right|$ is an increasing function in $x$ for fixed $n$, the minimum value occurs at a integer.  Let this i integer be $a$. Writing the sum as $\sum_{n=1}^{119} \left|nx-1\right|$, we have that for $x\le a$, the sum is
\begin{align*}
s(x) & = -x \sum_{n=1}^a n + a \sum_{n=1}^a n + \sum_{n=a+1}^{119} (nx-1) \\
& = -x\frac{a(a+1)}{2} + a\frac{a(a+1)}{2} + \frac{(119-a)(120-a)}{2} + x \frac{(a+1)(119-a)}{2} - \frac{(a+1)(119-a)}{2} \\
& =  60 - \frac{a^2 - 121a - 2380}{2x} < 60
\end{align*}
and for $x>a$, we have
\begin{align*}
s(x) & =   -x \sum_{n=1}^{119} n + \sum_{n=1}^a (nx-1) \\
&  = - \frac{x119(120)}{2} + a \frac{a+1}{2} + x \frac{a(a+1)}{2} - a \\
&   =  - \frac{a^2 - 121a + 2380}{2x}  < 60.
\end{align*}
Therefore the minimum must occur at $x=a$. Furthermore, since the expressions are symmetrical in $1,2,\ldots,119,$ all minimum values occur when $x = \frac{k+1}{2},$ where $k$ is odd. We have \begin{align*}s\left(\tfrac{119+1}{2}\right) & = \frac{120}{2} \cdot \frac{\left(\tfrac{119+1}{2}\right)-1}{2} = 60 \cdot 29.5 = \boxed{1770},  \\ s\left(\tfrac{133+1}{2}\right) & = \frac{108}{2} \cdot \frac{\left(\tfrac{133+1}{2}\right)-1}{2} = \boxed{3879}, \\ s\left(\tfrac{11+1}{2}\right) & =  \frac{6}{2} \cdot \frac{\left(\frac{11+1}{2}\right)-1}{2} = 3 \cdot 105 = \boxed{1785}.\end{align*}</answer>

problem:
The trapezoid shown has a height of length $12\text{ cm},$ a base of length $16\text{ cm},$ and an area of $162\text{ cm}^2.$ What is the perimeter of the trapezoid? [asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,12)--(11,12)--(16,0)--cycle);
label("12 cm",(-1,6),W);
draw((0.8,0)--(0.8,0.8)--(0,.8));
draw((0,11.2)--(0.8,11.2)--(0.8,12));
label("16 cm",(8,-1),S);
[/asy]

solution:
We first label the trapezoid $ABCD$ as shown in the diagram below. Since $AD$ is the height of the trapezoid, then $AB$ and $DC$ are parallel. The area of the trapezoid is \begin{align*}
\frac{AD}{2}\times(AB+DC)&=\frac{12}{2}\times(AB+16) \\
&=6\times(AB+16).
\end{align*} Since the area of the trapezoid is $162,$  we have $6\times(AB+16)=162$ so that $$AB+16=\frac{162}{6}.$$ Solving for $AB$, we obtain $AB=11.$

Construct a perpendicular from $B$ to $E$ on $DC.$ Since $AB$ and $DE$ are parallel, and both $AD$ and $BE$ are perpendicular to $DE,$ we know that $ABED$ is a rectangle. Thus, $DE=AB=11,$ $BE=AD=12,$ and \begin{align*}
EC&=DC-DE \\
&=16-11 \\
&=5.
\end{align*} Since $\angle BEC=90^{\circ},$ we know that $\triangle BEC$ is a right triangle. Thus by the Pythagorean Theorem, \begin{align*}
BC^2&=BE^2+EC^2 \\
&= 12^2+5^2 \\
&= 169
\end{align*} so that $BC=13$ (since $BC>0$).

The perimeter of the trapezoid is $$AB+BC+CD+DA=11+13+16+12=\boxed{52}\text{ cm}.$$ [asy]
draw((0,0)--(0,12)--(11,12)--(16,0)--cycle);
draw((11,0)--(11,12),dashed);
draw((11.7,0)--(11.7,.7)--(11,.7));
label("$A$",(0,12),NW);
label("$B$",(11,12),NE);
label("$C$",(16,0),SE);
label("$E$",(11,0),S);
label("$D$",(0,0),SW);
label("12 cm",(-1,6),W);
label("16 cm",(8,-1),S);
[/asy]

